Turn this button into a functional element. Inside there, you can set a UI state (disabled: false, for example), then you render the element using the disable state to conditionally render your component, like this:

    if(state.disabled){
    return (your button JSX without the onClick event);
    } else {
    return (your button JSX with the onClick event);
    }

You can use a onClickHandler to do the button job and set the state to remove the onClick event.

This is a fairly good question, but I think to keep the approach as close to idiomatic React as possible, you need to think in terms of _passing props_, not adding or removing event listeners. In your case, something like this:

    class Quiz extends React.Component {
      constructor(props) {
        super(props);
    
        this.state = {
          disableButton: false,
          score: 0
        };
    
        this.checkBtn = this.checkBtn.bind(this);
      }
    
      checkBtn(e) {
        if (e.target.value === &quot;1&quot;) {
          this.setState(state =&gt; ({
            disableButton: true,
            score: state.score + 1
          }));
        }
      }
    
      render() {
        const { disableButton } = this.state;
        return (
          &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;button value=&quot;1&quot; onClick={!disableButton &amp;&amp; this.checkBtn}&gt;
              first
            &lt;/button&gt;
            &lt;button value=&quot;2&quot; onClick={!disableButton &amp;&amp; this.checkBtn}&gt;
              second
            &lt;/button&gt;
    
            &lt;button value=&quot;1&quot; onClick={!disableButton &amp;&amp; this.checkBtn}&gt;
              first
            &lt;/button&gt;
            &lt;button value=&quot;2&quot; onClick={!disableButton &amp;&amp; this.checkBtn}&gt;
              second
            &lt;/button&gt;
    
            &lt;p&gt;{this.state.score}&lt;/p&gt;
          &lt;/div&gt;
        );
      }
    }

So you were close enough. Check out [the Codepen](https://codepen.io/rishatmuhametshin/pen/LYYYzaY?editors=1010) to see how it works.

I&#39;m not entirely sure if this really makes for a whole solution, but at least I hope if helps you move forward.

You can&#39;t remove an event listener in React but you can tell it which function to run based on state. It sounds like if the score&#39;s 1 you don&#39;t want the user to be able to activate the function on the buttons with the one value, for that I&#39;d change your render function to the below;

    render() {
        const { disableButton } = this.state;
        return (
          &lt;div&gt;
            &lt;button value=&quot;1&quot; onClick={this.state.score === 1 ? () =&gt; {} : this.checkBtn}&gt;first&lt;/button&gt;
             &lt;button value=&quot;2&quot; onClick={this.checkBtn}&gt;second&lt;/button&gt;
        
              &lt;button value=&quot;1&quot; onClick={this.state.score === 1 ? () =&gt; {} : this.checkBtn}&gt;first&lt;/button&gt;
             &lt;button value=&quot;2&quot; onClick={this.checkBtn}&gt;second&lt;/button&gt;
        
            &lt;p&gt;{this.state.score}&lt;/p&gt;
            &lt;/div&gt;
        );
      }

This way if the score is 1 it&#39;ll run an anonymous function that does nothing, otherwise it&#39;ll run checkBtn

